snippet.textDisplay: Ok Jeff, I think it's time for an Athlean-x minimalist program. First, thanks for this video. As someone who first experienced Jeff's world as a Zero athlete, I think having a program that incorporates the ideas of progressive overload and some minimal equipment like a pull-up bar would be excellent. For me, it's much more motivating to have a limit (like a minute) to push towards, even if I can't make it. It's more concrete than the command "go to fatigue". I always question whether I couldn't have pushed myself for one more rep.  But when you're halfway through your third set, it's hard to care sometimes. The progressive overload makes sure that there is a goal, and if you meet it, there's a bar that can be raised with the time. I feel that with something like a chinup bar and some bands there's another level that can be explored midway between a gym and having nothing at all. Again thanks for looking out for us all with the gym closed. I can still get into beast mode with this!

snippet.textDisplay:
First off: Jeff, you are an evil, evil man.

As for some end-user criticism from a guy who is reasonably fit and with decent coordination:

a) NONE of this is "novice" or "beginner" level. A lot of the movements are way too complex for a complete greenhorn at exercising to accomplish. And to top that off, most beginners will be done pretty much after exercise A in any set. To me, this is a workout for guys between "reasonably fit" and "in damn good shape".

b) Some of the exercises don't scale well with the others. The "easy" shoulder-exercise is fine, but it's about 20 times easier than handstand push-ups. In contrast, doing the ankle-squats with or without a kickstand is a relatively small progression, mostly with balance and coordination.

c) Three rounds of this are completely unachievable for anybody who isn't in really good shape. I had trouble with clean execution on the second round on a lot of exercises, even when I jumped down to the "easy" version to keep my reps clean in the middle of the minute.

d) For anybody who isn't really advanced at all of the individual exercises, the workout is gonna be WAY more than 35/50 minutes. If you pause the timer and rest at failure (to execute clean reps), you'll be doing that for a few minutes total, at least. Again, I'm neither super fit nor completely inept at this stuff. Workout A took me around 45 minutes, including rest-pauses and some time for referencing the exercises - with two rounds total.

For reference; I've been doing body-weight stuff consistently for around 3-3,5 hours each week for the past few years, in addition to 3-4 hours of sports of other kinds.. I don't (or rather, didn't) go super intense thus far, but I can do quite a few clean, controlled push-ups and other classical exercises.

And finally, thank you, Jeff, for providing excellent content every few days. The fitness community needs you, beginner to athlete. Thanks!
